"The opportunity cost is infinite to anywhere you place your limited resources. So the journey, or the evolution of money, of finding a money, has been to try to find something that mimics our limitations, that mimics the sacrifices we make when we bestow value on something."⁣
⁣
Another clip from my latest podcast (S4: E40) where we discuss and explore Bitcoin, crypto, and what it means for society with John Vallis, Gigi Der, Robert Breedlove, and Richard James.⁣
⁣
Watch more via the link in my bio.⁣
⁣
Recorded 05/13/2021.

node.title: Money Is A Measure of Sacrifice

“In order for value to emerge, we need to define limitations. Things are defined by their limitations.”⁣
⁣
On this episode of the Podcast, I sit down with four experienced Bitcoiners to chat about the future of crypto in today’s growing world. They discuss how to get started with Bitcoin, the advantages and disadvantages, as well as revealing the truth of the world.⁣
⁣
My guests are John Vallis, Gigi Der, Robert Breedlove, and Richard James.⁣
⁣
Watch this podcast (S4: E40) on YouTube via the link in my bio.⁣
⁣
Recorded 05/13/2021.

node.text:
"...I was reading a book called Hitler’s Table Talk, which was a collection of his spontaneous utterances at mealtimes collected over about three years. It really affected my reading of it, because the number of times he used parasite metaphors really stuck in my mind."⁣
⁣
"I started to look at all of the Nazi propaganda from before the Second World War in terms of parasite-stress hypothesis, especially after I also realized that Hitler’s extermination campaign arguably had its origins in public health policy because they started out with tuberculosis interventions. Then they went to “clean up” the mental hospitals, and so on."⁣
⁣
More of this podcast (S4 E38) is available via the link in my bio.⁣
⁣
Recorded 05/10/21.

node.title: Hitler’s Fear of Germs Shaped Nazi Propaganda

⁣
Recorded 04/14/2021.

What is the antidote to the suffering and malevolence of life? The highest possible goal.

What is the prerequisite to the pursuit of the highest possible goal? The willingness to adopt the maximum degree of responsibility.

You might object: “Why should I shoulder all that burden? It is nothing but sacrifice, hardship, and trouble.” But what makes you so sure you do not want something heavy to carry? You positively need to be occupied with something weighty, deep, profound, and difficult.

Your life becomes meaningful in precise proportion to the depths of the responsibility you are willing to shoulder.

What do you do if you're afraid and, to some degree, anxious?

You lay out what you're anxious about in detail. Ask yourself, "What it is that I'm afraid of that might happen?" Next, you deconstruct it into smaller increments - into hypothetically manageable problems - and then you expose yourself, gradually, to the thing that you're afraid of.

The effect of this is not that you become less afraid. What happens instead? You become braver. And that's not the same thing.

It's not like, "well, the world isn't as dangerous as I thought it was, you know, silly me." What happens, realistically, is, "yeah, the damn world's just as dangerous as I thought, or maybe it's even more dangerous than I thought. It turns out that there's something in me that responds to taking that on as a voluntary challenge and grows and thrives as a consequence."

To decide to move forward courageously into the land of the unknown. That's one of the secrets to a good life.
